      "writtenOn": "2026-03-09T19:26:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The simple answer is Ohm\u0027s Law: V \u003d I * R.  While an ADC typically measures voltage, you can use it to measure current by having a fixed resistor tied to the ADC pin.\n\nVendors have whole documents that describe how to use their hardware for voltage-based current sensing.  Ex. https://www.analog.com/en/resources/app-notes/an-105fa.html\n\nSo, while ADC measures \"Voltage\" if you know the circuit design you use it to measure \"Amperes\".  Right now we\u0027re having to create phosphor-virtual-sensors for each one of these, but it seems relatively straight-forward to just to it natively in dbus-sensors.",
      "parentUuid": "f3024b9d_3b386889",
      "revId": "6eb7017276078f4ca1212edef55cb7e2de80f2a5",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2e74e738_02e9daae",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 16,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000153
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-10T00:07:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Generally we\u0027d just expose this as a new Type rather than trying to define math and implement things in a config.  Having an ADC be able to expose a power sense resistor type seems reasonable, but just being able to randomly override any unit and requiring a user do the math seems unreasonable.  Is there a good reason for configs to allow this becoming a humidity value?  That\u0027s what it does today.\n\nMaybe we just add a \"ShuntResistorInOhms\" Property, and in ADCSensor we do the math?\n\nThis is not what I would recommend, but weren\u0027t the virtual sensors also supposed to solve this problem with expertk expressions?",
      "parentUuid": "75bbf98a_fb75aba0",
      "revId": "6eb7017276078f4ca1212edef55cb7e2de80f2a5",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
